User Authentication Design

Page summary

This design provides a secure and flexible way to handle user login and access control.

* Keycloak is used for authentication.
* CASPORT is used for authorization.
* The browser uses a secure session cookie and does not store access or refresh tokens.
* The Authentication Gateway handles login, logout, sessions, provider communication, and user identity mapping.
* Application APIs enforce access rules for every request.

The design is provider-neutral, so other OIDC, SAML, or authorization services can be added later without changing the UI or core application logic.

⸻

1. Architecture diagram

This diagram shows the main components.

The Browser UI communicates with the Authentication Gateway using secure /auth and /api endpoints.

The Authentication Gateway:

* handles login, logout, and callbacks;
* stores sessions securely;
* protects against CSRF;
* connects to authentication and authorization providers;
* converts provider-specific data into a standard application format.

Authentication adapters support Keycloak, generic OIDC, SAML, and future providers.

Authorization adapters support CASPORT, Keycloak roles, and other policy services.

Application APIs validate the user and enforce permissions.

⸻

2. Authorization-provider interface

This interface defines how the application works with CASPORT or another authorization service.

It performs three main tasks:

* resolvePrincipal — maps the authenticated user to an application user;
* getEntitlements — gets roles, groups, permissions, or attributes;
* authorize — checks whether the user can perform an action on a resource.

NormalizedPrincipal provides one standard user format, regardless of which provider supplied the data.

AuthorizationDecision returns:

* whether access is allowed;
* the reason for the decision;
* the policy version;
* when the decision expires.

⸻

3. Authentication-provider interface

This interface defines how the application works with Keycloak or another identity provider.

It supports:

* starting login;
* processing the login callback;
* refreshing credentials;
* logging out;
* reporting provider capabilities.

After login, the provider returns an ExternalIdentity containing information such as:

* provider;
* issuer;
* subject;
* username;
* email;
* authentication time;
* assurance level.

The application then maps this identity to its own internal user.

⸻

4. Configuration example

The configuration selects:

* Keycloak as the authentication provider;
* CASPORT as the authorization provider;
* Redis for server-side session storage;
* secure, HttpOnly session cookies;
* a fail-closed policy when CASPORT is unavailable.

The configuration also defines how a Keycloak user is matched to a CASPORT user.

A stable identifier such as employee ID is preferable to username or email.

⸻

5. Authentication flow

The user opens the application and selects a login provider.

The browser is redirected to Keycloak, where the user authenticates.

After successful login:

1. Keycloak redirects back to the Authentication Gateway.
2. The gateway validates the response.
3. The user identity is normalized.
4. CASPORT provides roles, attributes, or permissions.
5. A secure application session is created.
6. The user returns to the application.

If authentication fails, the user sees an error and can try again.

⸻

6. Sign-in screen

The sign-in screen provides buttons for configured identity providers.

The UI should only start the login process. It should not store tokens or call Keycloak or CASPORT directly.

A CASPORT sign-in button should only be shown if CASPORT actually authenticates users. If CASPORT is authorization-only, it should work in the background after Keycloak login.

Local email and password fields should only be included if the application is expected to manage its own user credentials.

